o/actions/workflows/ci.yml/badge.svg)](https://github.com/evo-hq/evo/actions/wor
kflows/ci.yml)\n    12\t[![DOI](https://zenodo.org/badge/DOI/10.5281/zenodo.2044
7923.svg)](https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.20447923)\n    13\t\n    14\t**Get sta
rted with autoresearch on any codebase - with two simple commands.**\n    15\t\n
   16\tDo you want to do more with autoresearch or need a custom, hands-on deplo
yment?\n    17\t[Request access to evo platform](https://evo-hq.com/beta) or ema
il [hello@evo-hq.com](mailto:hello@evo-hq.com).\n    18\t\n    19\t---\n    20\t
**[Try it](#try-it)** · **[Install](#install)** · **[How it works](#how-it-works
)** · **[Dashboard](#dashboard)** · **[Upgrading](#upgrading)**\n    21\t\n    2
2\t</div>\n    23\tA plugin for your agentic framework that optimizes code throu
gh experiments\n    24\t\n    25\tYou give it a codebase. It discovers metrics t
o optimize, sets up the evaluation, and starts running experiments in a loop -- 
trying things, keeping what improves the score, throwing away what doesn\'t.\n  
 26\t\n    27\t*Inspired by [Karpathy\'s autoresearch](https://github.com/karpat
hy/autoresearch)* -- where an LLM runs training experiments autonomously to beat
its own best score. Autoresearch is a pure hill climb: try something, keep or re
vert, repeat on a single branch. Evo adds structure on top of that idea:\n    28
\t\n    29\t- **Tree search over greedy hill climb.** Multiple directions can fo
rk from any committed node, so exploration doesn\'t collapse to one path.\n    3
0\t- **Parallel semi-autonomous agents.** Spawn multiple subagents and run them 
simultaneously, each in its own git worktree. Each subagent reads traces, formul
ates hypotheses, and can run multiple iterations within its branch.\n    31\t- *
*Shared state.** Failure traces, annotations, and discarded hypotheses are acces
sible to every agent before it decides what to try next.\n    32\t- **Gating.** 
Regression tests or safety checks can be wired up as a gate. Experiments that do
n\'t pass get discarded.\n    33\t- **Observability.** A dashboard to monitor yo
ur experiments.\n    34\t- **Benchmark discovery.** The `discover` skill explore
s the repo, figures out what to measure, and instruments the evaluation.\n    35
\t\n    36\t\n    37\tRuns on Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, Kimi, OpenClaw, Hermes
, Opencode, or Pi. Experiments run locally or on remote sandboxes — Modal, E2B, 
Daytona, AWS, Azure, SSH.\n    38\t\n    39\t\n    40\t<p align="center">\n    4
1\t  <img src="assets/dashboard.png" alt="evo dashboard" width="100%" />\n    42
\t</p>\n    43\t\n    44\t## Try it\n    45\t\n    46\tTwo commands:\n    47\t\n
   48\t```\n    49\t/evo:discover     # one-time code discovery: figures out ben
chmarks and creates gates against unintended changes\n    50\t/evo:optimize     
# run the loop\n    51\t```\n    52\t\n    53\t`discover` asks what to optimize,
the benchmark command, and the metric direction. Skip the questions by seeding t
he answer:\n    54\t\n    55\t```\n    56\t/evo:discover make the JSON parser at
src/parser.py faster\n    57\t```\n    58\t\n    59\tThen run the loop:\n    60\
t\n    61\t```\n    62\t/evo:optimize\n    63\t```\n    64\t\n    65\tevo sizes 
each round to your benchmark\'s resource profile — one experiment at a time when
a run needs the whole GPU or another exclusive resource, wider when runs are ind
ependent — and keeps going until the score stops improving. By default it runs u
nattended and pushes edits through parallel subagents; say so in plain language 
if you\'d rather it pause after each round or hold to one experiment at a time.\
n    66\t\n    67\tInvocation syntax is host-specific: `/evo:` on Claude Code, `
$evo` on Codex, `/` skill menu on Cursor, natural language on Hermes, Opencode, 
OpenClaw, and Pi.\n    68\t\n    69\t## Install\n    70\t\n    71\t```bash\n    
72\t# 1. evo CLI\n    73\tuv tool install evo-hq-cli\n    74\t\n    75\t# 2. Hos
t CLI (if you don\'t already have it)\n    76\tnpm install -g @anthropic-ai/clau
de-code     # or @openai/codex, openclaw, @earendil-works/pi-coding-agent\n    7
7\t# Cursor: install from cursor.com (IDE), or `curl https://cursor.com/install 
-fsS | bash` for the cursor-agent CLI\n    78\t# Kimi: `curl -fsSL https://code.
kimi.com/install.sh | bash`, or `npm install -g @moonshot-ai/kimi-code`\n    79\
t\n    80\t# 3. Plugin + host hooks\n    81\tevo install <host>     # claude-cod
e | codex | cursor | hermes | kimi | opencode | openclaw | pi\n    82\t```\n    
83\t\n    84\tFor remote backends, install with the matching provider extra: `uv
tool install \'evo-hq-cli[modal]\'` (or `[e2b]`, `[daytona]`, `[aws]`, `[azure]`
, `[all]`).\n    85\t\n    86\t### Codex hook trust\n    87\t\n    88\t`evo inst
all codex` trusts evo\'s hooks for you. To review them yourself first, pass `--n
o-trust-hooks`, then approve via `/hooks` inside codex.\n    89\t\n    90\t## Ho
w it works\n    91\t\n    92\t### Parallel\n    93\t\n    94\tThe orchestrator d
ispatches subagents in parallel. Each runs in its own isolated workspace, picks 
up shared state (failure traces, annotations, discarded hypotheses), forms a hyp
othesis, edits, and runs the benchmark. A subagent with iteration budget remaini
ng continues on its branch within the same round when its prior edit warrants a 
follow-up.\n    95\t\n    96\t### Frontier strategy\n    97\t\n    98\tAfter eac
h round, the orchestrator selects which committed branch to extend next. Availab
le strategies:\n    99\t\n   100\t- **argmax** — extend the highest-scoring bran
ch\n   101\t- **top_k** — round-robin among the K best\n   102\t- **epsilon_gree
dy** — best most of the time, random sometimes\n   103\t- **softmax** — sample w
eighted by score\n   104\t- **pareto_per_task** — keep specialists the aggregate
hides, inspired by [GEPA](https://arxiv.org/abs/2507.19457)\n   105\t\n   106\tC
onfigure in the dashboard\'s Frontier tab, which lists each strategy\'s paramete
rs.\n   107\t\n   108\t### Cross-cutting scans\n   109\t\n   110\tBetween rounds
, [RLM](https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.24601)-inspired scan subagents read trace bat
ches in parallel and surface compound failure patterns: gate-failure intersectio
ns, shared root causes across traces. Findings land in shared state, which the n
ext round\'s subagents read at startup.\n   111\t\n   112\t### Gates\n   113\t\n
  114\tevo introduces **gates**: pass/fail checks that run on every experiment. 
An experiment that fails a gate is discarded even if its score beats the current
best. Without gates, the search will find ways to return a constant, skip work, 
or trade correctness for speed.\n   115\t\n   116\tAny command that exits zero o
n pass and non-zero on fail qualifies as a gate: a test suite, an invariant scri
pt, a score floor on a held-out slice of the benchmark. Gates inherit down the e
xperiment tree: a gate registered at the root runs on every descendant. Narrower
gates can be attached to specific branches.\n   117\t\n   118\tWhen `discover` b
uilds a benchmark from scratch, it attaches a held-out-slice score-floor gate au
tomatically. When the benchmark already exists in the repo, gates are opt-in.\n 
 119\t\n   120\t## Where experiments run\n   121\t\n   122\t| Backend | Where | 
Install |\n   123\t|---|---|---|\n   124\t| **worktree** *(default)* | local git
worktree per experiment | included |\n   125\t| **pool** | reuse a fixed set of 
local workspaces | included |\n   126\t| **ssh** | your own SSH host | included 
|\n   127\t| **modal** | Modal serverless cloud | `uv tool install \'evo-hq-cli[
modal]\'` |\n   128\t| **e2b** | E2B cloud sandboxes | `uv tool install \'evo-hq
-cli[e2b]\'` |\n   129\t| **daytona** | Daytona cloud workspaces | `uv tool inst
all \'evo-hq-cli[daytona]\'` |\n   130\t| **aws** | AWS EC2 sandboxes | `uv tool
install \'evo-hq-cli[aws]\'` |\n   131\t| **azure** | Azure VMs | `uv tool insta
ll \'evo-hq-cli[azure]\'` |\n   132\t\n   133\tPick and configure in the dashboa
rd\'s Backend tab.\n   134\t\n   135\t## Dashboard\n   136\t\n   137\tThe dashbo
ard starts automatically with `/evo:discover` (or `evo init`) and prints the URL
in chat:\n   138\t\n   139\t```\n   140\tDashboard live: http://127.0.0.1:8080 (
pid 12345)\n   141\t```\n   142\t\n   143\tIf `8080` is in use, evo increments t
o the next free port (`8081`, `8082`, …) and prints it. Subsequent runs reuse th
e chosen port. Start it manually with:\n   144\t\n   145\t```bash\n   146\tuv ru
n --project /path/to/evo/plugins/evo evo dashboard --port 8080\n   147\t```\n   
148\t\n   149\t## Upgrading\n   150\t\n   151\t```bash\n   152\tevo update      
                    # update CLI + every installed host\n   153\tevo update <hos
t>                    # update one host (also bumps CLI to match)\n   154\tevo u
pdate <host> --version 0.4.1    # pin to a release\n   155\t```\n   156\t\n   15
7\tEvery `evo install` / `evo update` keeps the CLI on PATH in lockstep with the
host plugin version it just installed (`uv tool install --force evo-hq-cli` unde
r the hood). Without a `--version` pin that resolves to the latest **stable** re
lease, so running an unpinned `evo install`/`evo update` against a pre-release p
ulls the CLI back to stable — pin both sides for an alpha (see [Testing a pre-re
lease](#testing-a-pre-release-alpha)). The CLI binary, the skill files, and the 
hook protocol share wire formats — letting them drift caused silent failures in 
earlier versions. Editable installs (`uv tool install --editable`, `pip install 
-e`) are detected and left untouched.\n   158\t\n   159\tSee `evo update --help`
for `--force`, `--scope`, and additional flags.\n   160\t\n   161\t### Migrating
from any pre-0.4.4 version\n   162\t\n   163\t```bash\n   164\tuv tool install -
-force evo-hq-cli && evo update --force\n   165\t```\n   166\t\n   167\t`--force
` wipes the host plugin cache and reinstalls, working around [anthropics/claude-
code#14061](https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code/issues/14061): `/plugin up
date` returns success but does not replace cached plugin files.\n   168\t\n   16
9\t### Hooks failing with exit 127\n   170\t\n   171\tThe host lost evo\'s hook 
binary. Fixed in 0.5.1; reinstall the host to repair:\n   172\t\n   173\t```bash
\n   174\tuv tool install --force evo-hq-cli && evo install codex --force   # or
: evo install claude-code --force\n   175\t```\n   176\t\n   177\t`evo doctor <h
ost>` confirms the result.\n   178\t\n   179\t### Testing a pre-release (alpha)\
n   180\t\n   181\t`uv` and `pip` skip pre-releases by default. To install an al
pha, pin both the CLI version and the host plugin tag:\n   182\t\n   183\t```bas
h\n   184\tuv tool install --force \'evo-hq-cli==0.4.1a2\' && \\\n   185\t  evo 
update --version 0.4.1-alpha.2 --force\n   186\t```\n   187\t\n   188\tSubstitut
e the target alpha version. The CLI uses PEP 440 form (`0.4.1a2`); the marketpla
ce tag uses the dash form (`v0.4.1-alpha.2`).\n   189\t\n   190\t## Telemetry\n 
 191\t\n   192\tevo sends anonymous telemetry and usage stats that helps us impr
ove evo.\n   193\tDisable it globally anytime:\n   194\t\n   195\t```bash\n   19
6\tevo telemetry off\n   197\t```\n   198\t\n   199\tOr for one command/session:
